  "title": "Maternal Love and Hatred",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "457a637b18ceb0a0",
      "text": "The followers of [[Melanie Klein]]'s school go much further back in the history of the individual. They see the development of the psychological structures that can be used for war in early childhood, i.e. in the \"pre-oedipal phase\". The \"paranoia theory of war\" belongs in this context. It follows Melanie Klein's view that the mother serves the child as a vessel for all good things as well as for all bad things. This can be traced back to the fact that the infant does not begin with ready-made ideas of other people, but that its world initially consists of isolated parts (breast, hands, etc.). They are associated with the child's own feelings towards these objects. To the extent that it loves them, it experiences them as benevolent, and to the extent that it is aggressive towards them, it experiences them as malicious. The child introjects and projects the fairy tales and witches it has created itself, with the help of which it personalizes pleasure and displeasure.46 If it is persecuted by externalized \"witches\", then one speaks of persecution anxiety, since it feels persecuted by an enemy that it has, however, created itself. Money-Kyrle, one of the most prominent representatives of this theory, calls the process by which the child identifies with the internalized evil object, the enemy, the \"manic process \"47. It gives a feeling of strength. In his view, it is the prototype of the psychological mechanism responsible for choosing the option of war.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "81b4f02f33e6845c",
      "text": "War occurs because real differences are not seen realistically, but are distorted. \"Here I would like to emphasize that the creation of a radically destructive relationship to the other is one of the most typical aspects of hatred and war as a delusion of persecution. In the experience of love, the existence of the other is indispensable for the self, which can go so far as to become a constituent part of the self. In the experience of hate, the existence of the other is experienced as a negation of the existence of the self.\"\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "d905520c57db80c0",
      "text": "Fornari's explanation can also be classified in the tradition of Melanie Klein. His thesis is that war is caused by the \"paranoid elaboration of grief\". Its function is to heal the paranoid and depressive fears that are inherent in every human being. War is like an iceberg, the smaller part of which can be observed on the surface, while the larger part remains hidden. On the surface, it serves as a defense against external dangers, while unconsciously it serves as a defense and security maneuver against terrifying fantasy entities (terrifiers) that are not flesh and blood and represent an absolute danger (as in nightmares)."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "069929995098345c",
      "text": "War serves more to defend against and protect against this internal enemy than the external one. The psychological manoeuvre by which a frightening but unconquerable and invulnerable inner entity - the terrifier - is transformed into an external enemy made of flesh and blood can be understood as externalization and/or personalization. War is a form of organization that provides security, not because it allows defence against external enemies, but because it makes it possible to find or invent real enemies that can be killed. Without war, society would be helplessly at the mercy of this internal enemy. This leads to the incredible paradox that its most important security function is not defense against external enemies, but finding real enemies.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "6a20aa9d3db183f4",
      "text": "Quintessence: If we find someone or something bad in the outside world that we can destroy, we can protect ourselves both from being hurt by this evil (persecutory fears) and from the danger of aggression against something we love, for example a good, protective object (depressive fears).\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "8e78d0d52a469bf8",
      "text": "It seems that the function of this whole system is to control the uncontrollable by projecting an internal psychotic fear into a real external danger.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "2ac599dd9bff4ca2",
      "text": "Fornari's explanation for this mechanism is that we – all of us – equate the separation from the love object (the mother) with his (her) death and feel guilty about our sadistic fantasies towards him (her). If we attribute the guilt to the magical powers of the enemy, we are freed from our feelings of guilt.\n"
    }
